<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Attend Memorial Ceremony for Pediatrician </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leaders Attend Memorial Ceremony for Pediatrician </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1005163394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1619 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1005163394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 10 (XINHUA) -- A farewell ceremony was 
held here today for Zhu Futang, a well-known pediatrician and an 
academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, who died on 
April 23 at the age of 95. 
  More than 600 people, including Chen Xitong, member of the 
Politbureau of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of 
China (CPC), Chen Muhua, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee 
of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), and Chen 
Minzhang, minister of public health, attended the ceremony. 
  Founder of China's modern pediatrics, Zhu was also an 
educator and honorary president of the Beijing Children's 
Hospital. 
  A native of Wuxi city in east China's Jiangsu Province, he 
graduated from the Beijing Union Medical College in 1927 and 
obtained a doctor's degree from the State University of New York 
of the United States. 
  In 1931 he went to the United States to study pediatrics, 
majoring in the prevention of children's measles through 
placental globulin, and was highly praised by TIME magazine at 
that time. 
  Zhu's achievements in that study are still helping 
pediatricians in many hospitals around the world today. 
  He returned to China in 1933 and with others set up the 
private Beijing Pediatrics Hospital in 1942. 
  In the 1960s, he and other Chinese pediatricians invented a 
new vaccine for measles and promoted it across the nation. The 
vaccine effectively reduced the occurrence of and mortality rate 
from children's measles in China. 
  His work Practical Pediatrics, which was first 
published in 1943, was highly praised by fellow pediatricians 
around the world. In 1993, that book was awarded a national best 
prize. 
  He also set up a training seminar, through which several 
generations of pediatricians in China were trained. In 1991, 
the ministry of public health set up the "Zhu Futang Prize" in 
his honor, an award to recognize outstanding pediatricians in 
China annually. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

