<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deng Pufang Speaks to Press on Humanitarianism, Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deng Pufang Speaks to Press on Humanitarianism, Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Claims `Dramatic Changes' in China </H4>

<F P=102> HK1005124994 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 1009 GMT 
10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1005124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 10 (CNS) -- Chairman of the Chinese 
Association for the Handicapped Mr. Deng Pufang said that to 
talk of humanitarianism and human rights without taking into 
account clothing and food problems was insincere and unrealistic. 
  In a press conference on a sports meeting for the 
handicapped 
in the Far East and South Pacific region, Mr. Deng, the son of 
Deng Xiaoping, made these remarks in reply to a question on the 
relationship between humanitarianism and human rights. He said 
that humanitarianism and human rights were closely related with 
the former regarded as an ideal to be sought for which covers 
the fact that every person is entitled to enjoy the rights of 
man and humanitarianism can help realize the value of mankind. 
He added that China put a strong emphasis on humanitarianism 
and human rights. During the last few years China did its very 
best to protect the rights and interests of the handicapped. 
  With China's reform and open door policy going further, Mr. 
Deng said that the living standard of the general public was 
becoming better while that of the handicapped was improving 
gradually. He added that there had been dramatic changes in 
China in the past few years when people's lives took a turn for 
the better. People could achieve their goal and hopes through 
their own efforts. 
  Mr. Deng pointed out that generally speaking the living 
standard for handicapped people in China had to some extent 
improved while many disabled people were still facing various 
kinds of difficulties including clothing and food problems with 
their economic life in no way guaranteed. 

</TEXT>

