<H3> <TI>   Deng Pufang Speaks to Press on Humanitarianism, Rights </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deng Pufang Speaks to Press on Humanitarianism, Rights </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Expresses Desire To Visit Taiwan </H4>

<F P=102> OW1105014694 Beijing Central Television Program One Network 
in Mandarin 1430 GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1105014694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing Central Television Program One Network 
in Mandarin 1430 GMT 10 May 94 </F>

<F P=105> Mandarin </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [News conference by Deng Pufang, president of the Chinese </F>
Federation for the Disabled and chairman of the Preparatory 
Committee for the Sixth Far East and South Pacific Games for the 
Disabled; Zhang Baifa, executive vice chairman of the 
preparatory committee and vice mayor of Beijing; and Wan Siquan, 
secretary general of the preparatory committee, with foreign and 
domestic correspondents in Beijing on 10 May, hosted by the 
State Council Information Office -- recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Announcer] A ZHONGGUO 
XINWEN SHE correspondent asked Deng Pufang for his comments 
about the first gathering in Beijing of disabled athletes from 
both sides of the Taiwan Straits as well as from Hong Kong and 
Macao. 
  [Deng] Both comrades from the Preparatory Committee and 
myself are delighted that athletes from Hong Kong, Macao, and 
Taiwan will be participating in the games. On the one hand, the 
Preparatory Committee will try its best to serve them and make 
them feel at home. On the other, I wish them good results. I 
shall be as delighted if they achieve good results as I shall be 
if mainland- based disabled athletes do the same. 
  [Announcer] Taibei's [Taipei] CENTRAL NEWS AGENCY would like 
to ask Deng two questions. The first is whether you have any 
plans to visit Taiwan in the near future. The second is what 
expectations you have regarding exchanges between disabled 
athletes from the two sides of the Taiwan Straits. 
  [Deng] I very much hope to visit Taiwan because Taiwan is 
part of China's territory. I am now seeking an opportunity to 
visit. Once conditions are right, I will definitely visit 
Taiwan. We also have had many contacts with Taiwan's disabled 
in recent years. We will continue such contacts and exchanges. 
In my opinion, contacts between the disabled are least 
susceptible to interference and influence from other factors. 
My disabled friends in Taiwan and myself share this common 
understanding and wish. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

