<H3> <TI>   State Council Approves Security Law Regulations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    State Council Approves Security Law Regulations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1005153394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1458 GMT 10 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1005153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, may 10 (XINHUA) -- An executive meeting of 
the State Council, China's highest governing body, today 
approved in principle a set of draft detailed regulations for 
the implementation of China's State Security Law. 
  Participants in the meeting, presided over by Premier Li 
Peng, decided that the draft regulations will be revised before 
being issued by the State Council. 
  They agreed that since coming into force on February 22, 
1992, the State Security Law has played a significant role in 
maintaining state security, defending the people's democratic 
dictatorship and the socialist system, and ensuring the progress 
of the reform, opening-up and socialist modernization drive. 
  The formulation of the detailed regulations is needed to 
enforce the law more effectively, they noted. 

</TEXT>

