<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Holds Weekly News Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Holds Weekly News Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Denies Mediating Role on Koreas </H4>

<F P=102> SK1205114194 Seoul YONHAP in English 1135 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1205114194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 12 (YONHAP) -- The Chinese Government 
on Thursday [12 May] denied some reports that China has been 
arranging behind the curtain a summit meeting between the two 
Koreas. 
  In a weekly press interview here, Wu Jianmin, Foreign 
Ministry spokesman, said China does not need to mediate between 
South and North Korea inasmuch as there is a dialogue channel 
between the two Koreas. 
  "The Chinese Government wishes to see South and North Korea 
resolve their problems through their direct and constructive 
dialogue and negotiations," Wu said. 
  Asked to comment on the report of North Korea's acceptance 
of 
nuclear inspection by the International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA), Wu said he heard nothing about it. 
  He added, however, that if the report were true, it could be 
a welcome news. "It is in accord with China's consistent policy 
that problems should be settled through dialogue and 
negotiations between direct parties involved," he said. 
  On the remarks allegedly made by a senior U.S. State 
Department official to the effect that China had assisted in 
North Korea's missile system and nuclear development, Wu 
rejected it as an "irresponsible and totally unfounded 
allegation." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

