<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-092 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sutherland on China's Entry Into GATT </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sutherland on China's Entry Into GATT </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1105145794 Beijing XINHUA in English 1431 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1105145794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 11 (XINHUA) -- Peter Sutherland, 
director-general of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade 
(GATT), said here today that he confides in the prospect of 
early completion of the negotiations on the terms and conditions 
for China's rejoining GATT. 
  "China's ambitious program of trade and economic reforms has 
contributed greatly to bringing China more closely into line 
with the world trading system," he told the 1994 China summit 
meeting which opened here today. 
  In his speech entitled "Global Multilateral Trading System: 
The Role of the People's Republic of China," he said that 
observing the Chinese economy in the process of reform, one 
could see that China is essentially doing "autonomously" what 
the world trade organization would in any case oblige it to do. 
  "China is to be congratulated on its most recently announced 
program of liberalization and reform," he said, since "China's 
economic reforms have given a far greater role to market forces 
and have led to a rapid liberalization of its foreign trade 
regime. 
  "I am sure that producers, traders and consumers the world 
over, including those in China, are keen to see full 
implementation of these and other announced reforms." 
  He said that given the magnitude of China's economy and the 
likelihood that China would assume a leading role in shaping the 
global economic environment of the next century, it was of 
critical importance that close attention be paid to the manner 
in which China proceeds with its full integration into the world 
trade organization. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

