<H3> <TI>   Li Lanqing Addresses Symposium on Foreign Trade Strategy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Li Lanqing Addresses Symposium on Foreign Trade Strategy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1105133294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1247 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1105133294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 11 (XINHUA) -- To become one of the 
world's 10 largest traders, China is to strive for a new foreign 
trade system with improved legislative protection, more 
transparency and open and fair competition. 
  The statement was made by Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing at 
the international symposium on China's strategy for foreign 
economy and trade opened here today. 
  Former U.S. Secretary of State Henry Kissinger and Director 
General of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) 
Peter Sutherland made speeches at the symposium. 
  This is the first symposium of its kind to be held in China. 
  In his speeches, Li said that China's foreign trade strategy 
is of vital importance to China's modernization drive as well as 
to the Asian and world economies, for China has a large 
population, a vast market and rich resources. 
  He said that China has made active contributions to the 
world 
economy and trade with the speeding up of China's economic 
development and expansion of its opening since the '80s, which 
has drawn attention from all over the world. 
  He continued that in the latter half of the '90s, China's 
economy will maintain sustained, fast and healthy development 
and China's market will be more open, so China will continue to 
make its due contributions to the world economy. 
  Wu Yi, minister of China's foreign trade and economic 
cooperation, said in her report at the symposium that although 
China's foreign trade has achieved substantial development, it 
can not fully meet the requirements of China's modernization 
construction, adding that China's foreign trade has a vast 
potential. 
  Wu gave a detailed description of China's foreign trade in 
her report titled "Opportunities and Prospects: Basic Framework 
for China's Foreign Trade in the 1990s". 
  She pointed out that China's economy is to be brought 
further 
in line with international practices and China will learn from 
successful international experience to formulate a suitable 
foreign trade strategy so as to ensure its development. 
  Before the opening of the symposium, Chinese Vice-Premier Li 
Lanqing met with some foreign attendants. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

