<H3> <TI>   More on Li Lanqing's Comments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    More on Li Lanqing's Comments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1105132494 Beijing XINHUA in English 1304 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1105132494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 11 (XINHUA) -- China today expressed 
its firm determination to take part in the world multi-lateral 
trade system. 
  At the international symposium on China's strategy for 
foreign economy and trade in the 1990s opened [as received] here 
today, Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing said that China is 
expecting to resume its status as a signatory country of the 
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) at an early date 
and become a founding member of the World Trade Organization 
(WTO). 
  In his speech, Li noted that China, along with other 
countries in the world, will continue to make efforts to 
strengthen a multi-lateral trade system in the world and 
maintain an open world trade environment. 
  Li expressed his hope that on the basis of the multi-lateral 
trade system, China will further its economic and trade 
relations with other countries so as to make its due 
contributions to the world economy. 
  In her report, Wu Yi, minister of Chinese foreign trade and 
economic cooperation, said that China resolutely advocates the 
multi-lateral trade system represented by GATT and is speeding 
up negotiations on its re-entry into GATT, adding that China's 
determination to re-enter GATT is firm and China has made great 
efforts to this end. 
  In accordance with international trade norms and practices, 
she said that China has conducted a series of reforms of its 
foreign trade system such as the improvement of conditions on 
market access and foreign trade transparency. 
  Wu noted that China's more open market plays an active role 
in the world economy and trade, and through reforms this year, 
China's economy and trade will be further brought in line with 
international rules. 
  Wu expressed her thanks to most contracting parties who 
support China for its re-entry into GATT. 
  Meanwhile, she hoped that some contracting parties can 
realize their commitments and take action to support China in 
the bid. 

</TEXT>

