<H3> <TI>   Leading U.S. Retailer Walmart Eyes Tianjin Market </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leading U.S. Retailer Walmart Eyes Tianjin Market </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1205015994 Beijing XINHUA in English 0103 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1205015994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tianjin, May 12 (XINHUA) -- The Walmart Company, a 
leading retailer of the United States, is studying the 
possibility of entering the Chinese retail market, according to 
the chairman of the board of directors of the company. 
  Robson Walton, whose company's retail sales volume tops 55 
billion U.S. dollars annually, has arrived in Tianjin to 
investigate market potential. 
  He said he is very much interested in China's huge market 
potential and is looking for investment possibilities in the 
north China port city. 
  The chairman has inspected several large commercial centers 
in the city and conducted in-depth discussions with local 
officials. 
  Tianjin, one of the leading trade and commercial centers in 
northern China and one of the few cities that allow foreign 
investment in commerce and retail sales, has become the favorite 
of many foreign investors. 
  The Isetan Company of Japan, which leased and opened a large 
shopping center in the city last year, is achieving a rising 
business volume. Another large store funded by a Hong Kong 
company is also being constructed. 
  Other overseas businessmen eyeing Tianjin market potentials 
include the Chia Tai Group company of Thailand and the Nino 
Textile Company of Germany, local officials revealed. 

</TEXT>

