<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cambodia's Sihanouk `Suddenly' Announces Trip </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cambodia's Sihanouk `Suddenly' Announces Trip </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1105153394 Beijing XINHUA in English 1514 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1105153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Phnom Penh, May 11 (XINHUA) - King Norodom Sihanouk 
of Cambodia announced suddenly today that he will leave for 
China on May 18 to resume chemotherapy treatment for cancer. 
  A statement released by the royal palace said the reason the 
king is going to China earlier than planned is because he has 
been "slandered" over his latest proposals for peace. 
  Some local newspapers have recently accused the king of 
seeking to regain power by proposing new elections. 
  "From now on, I quit concerning myself with this tragic 
problem between the royal government and the Democratic 
Kampuchea Party. I don't want people to continue to slander 
me," the king, who repeatedly sought a peaceful solution to the 
civil war, said in a written statement. 
  In order to end the civil war and realize peace and national 
reconciliation in the country, Sihanouk proposed holding an 
early election to give the Democratic Kampuchea Party a chance 
to join the government. 
  On May 9, Khieu Samphan wrote to Sihanouk saying that he 
supported the proposal, but the government did not give a 
positive response. Some officials expressed the view that the 
term of the present government has yet expired, and that there 
are no fund available for another national election. 

</TEXT>

