<F P=100> Southeast Asia &amp; Pacific </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mahathir Backs Resistance to West </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mahathir Backs Resistance to West </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1105113194 Hong Kong AFP in English 1037 GMT 11 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK1105113194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, May 11 (AFP)--Malaysian Prime Minister 
Mahathir bin Mohamad on Wednesday offered strong support for the 
Chinese government's resistance to western pressure to change 
its social and political policies. 
  "China needs the strong government that it has. It may be 
authoritarian, but it is better than anarchy," said Mahathir. 
"Business needs order," he declared. 
  "For the moment the interest of the majority demands an 
orderly society," he said in a speech at a two-day international 
conference here on the "socialist market economy." 
  Mahathir advocated controlled development of a market 
economy. He said "it is right in not attempting a radical 
political about- turn simultaneously" with economic reforms. 
  The Malaysian premier strongly criticised western countries 
and accused them of wanting to weaken China. "This 
proselytising for democracy veils only slightly the objective of 
eliminating competition before it begins," he said. "They would 
like the East Asian democracies to be weak and unstable like 
theirs," he said, denouncing proposals by some nations for a 
worldwide minimum wage clause in the final text of the General 
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT). 
  Mahathir said he supported a strong China, which he 
described 
as an "engine of growth firstly for East Asia, including 
Southeast Asia, and the world." "Southeast Asia should have no 
fear of a wealthy and strong China." 

</TEXT>

