Daily Report 
<DATE1>  7 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Latin America &amp; Caribbean </F>
<H3> <TI>   Envoy to UN Discusses Beijing's Stand on Haiti Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Envoy to UN Discusses Beijing's Stand on Haiti Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0805100494 Beijing Central People's Radio Network in 
Mandarin 1030 GMT 7 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW0805100494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing Central People's Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Mandarin </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Hookup" program] </F>
  [Text] The UN Security Council yesterday unanimously 
adopted a resolution on imposing further economic sanctions 
against Haiti. The resolution will come into force at 0000 on 22 
May. The resolution calls on various countries to forbid all 
imports from and exports to Haiti with the exception of food, 
medicine, and items for humanitarian purposes. It also calls 
for banning air and sea transportation to Haiti except scheduled 
transportation for passengers. The resolution emphatically 
points out that the UN Security Council will remove all 
sanctions against Haiti only when Haiti's military rulers step 
down and the executive power of Aristide, the democratically 
elected president of Haiti, is returned and restored. 
  The UN Security Council resolution was proposed by the 
United 
States, France, Argentina, and other countries. 
  China maintains its reservations, although China voted for 
the resolution. Chen Jian, deputy representative of China's 
permanent mission to the United Nations, emphatically pointed 
out in his speech that China's persistent stand is not in favor 
of using sanctions as a method to resolve conflicts. The 
sanctions measure included in the resolution is a special 
measure to be taken under the extremely special situation in 
Haiti at present. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

