<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Property Rights Transfer Program Being Drafted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Property Rights Transfer Program Being Drafted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1205075894 Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE in Chinese 0605 
GMT 12 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1205075894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 12 May (ZHONGGUO TONGXUN SHE)--News from 
the China State Information Center indicates that the State 
Structural Reform Commission is drafting a program for 
transferring state-owned enterprises' property rights in order 
to standardize the practice of property rights transfer. 
  The individual revealed that the central government is 
encouraging small state-owned enterprises to transfer their 
property rights and affirmed that there are no ideological 
obstacles, even to the transfer of large and medium state-owned 
enterprises' property rights. Because China's economic 
construction is suffering a serious capital shortage, the income 
from transferring property rights will be used in urgent and 
important sectors of the national economy. Therefore, state 
asset losses will not be a problem as property rights are 
transferred; on the contrary, the transformation of tangible 
assets into monetary assets will be quite beneficial to an 
industrial adjustment. 
  An expert pointed out that the following merits attention in 
any discussion of property rights transfer: State assets should 
be scientifically and correctly appraised; payments should be 
made in a lump and no installments are allowed; asset ownership 
should be clearly defined; and, after an enterprise transfers 
its property rights, overall arrangements should be made for its 
staff members' and workers' employment and labor insurance and 
the pensions of its retired personnel. 

</TEXT>

