<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Firms May Bid For Infrastructure Projects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Firms May Bid For Infrastructure Projects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1205075994 Hong Kong LIEN HO PAO in Chinese 12 May 94 p 21 </F>
<F P=103> HK1205075994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong LIEN HO PAO </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Special dispatch": "Mainland China To Allow Foreign </F>
Businessmen To Contract For Major Capital Construction Projects"] 
  [Text] Beijing, 11 May--According to a relevant quarter, a 
Chinese department has formulated a new policy under which 
foreign businessmen will be allowed to invest or contract for 
some major infrastructure projects. After their completion, the 
projects will be managed and operated by the foreign businessmen 
during the contract period, which lasts 15 years or so, and the 
Chinese side will collect taxes. At the expiration of the 
contract period, the entire projects will be returned to the 
Chinese side. According to a briefing, foreign investors can 
have access to power plants, railways, highways, and other 
fields. Not only will they be allowed to undertake projects, 
they will also provide technology, equipment, and managerial 
personnel. 
  The authorities will also allow foreign businessmen to 
participate in project-related items, such as commerce, real 
estate, advertising, and other tertiary industry along the 
express highways and railways. 

</TEXT>

