<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Private Sector Prospering in Guangdong Province </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Private Sector Prospering in Guangdong Province </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1205023194 Beijing XINHUA in English 0136 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1205023194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Guangzhou, May 12 (XINHUA) -- The shift to a market 
economy has helped speed up the growth of the private sector in 
south China's Guangdong Province, according to the provincial 
administration for industry and commerce. 
  An administration official said that during the first 
quarter 
of 1994, 4,484 private companies were set up throughout 
Guangdong, a national pace-setter in reforms and opening to the 
outside world. 
  That figure brought the number of private companies in 
Guangdong to 50,000, 10.5 percent more than at the end of 1993, 
the official said. 
  He said that Guangdong had 25,000 private companies at the 
end of 1991, adding that 7,070 more such companies sprang up in 
the following year. 
  Last year saw the establishment of 13,000 such companies, he 
said. 
  Private companies have a total registered capital of 21.3 
billion yuan. "These companies have become a main force behind 
Guangdong's economic growth," he said. 
  Guangdong has some 4,000 private companies with a registered 
capital exceeding one million yuan each, he said. 
  To date, 40 private enterprise groups have been formed 
throughout Guangdong, he added. 
  According to the official, many government employees have 
abandoned their iron rice bowls, or lifelong jobs, to launch 
their own companies to provide services in advertising, real 
estate development, computers and consultancy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

