<F P=100> Central-South Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Residents Along Hubei Reservoirs Prosper </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Residents Along Hubei Reservoirs Prosper </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1205021794 Beijing XINHUA in English 0131 GMT 12 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1205021794 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Wuhan, may 12 (XINHUA) -- Residents along large 
reservoirs in central China's Hubei Province have become 
prosperous as local governments have adopted preferential 
policies to encourage them to develop a commodity economy. 
  Statistics show that the 45 large reservoir areas directly 
administered by the provincial government generated 530 million 
yuan in industrial and agricultural output value last year, 
compared with 360 million yuan in 1990. 
  The per capita net income of local residents also increased 
drastically. Most of the farmers living in the reservoir areas 
have now gotten enough to eat and wear. 
  While earmarking more money to support construction of basic 
facilities, such as farmland and water-control works to improve 
production and living conditions for local farmers, the 
provincial government has also adopted measures to encourage 
farmers in the above-mentioned areas to turn rich resources into 
economic advantages. 
  Local farmers have now established many cash forest areas, 
fish ponds, fenced streams for breeding fish, and bases for 
growing edible fungus, while making active efforts to set up 
numerous industrial businesses compatible with these bases. 
  Such efforts have begun to pay off. With more money in hand, 
farmers in the reservoir areas in turn have started to pursue 
more and better cultural activities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

