<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Lilian Wu] </F>
  [Text] Taipei, May 12 (CNA) -- Taiwan is seeking to boost 
trade with Southeast Asian nations by signing double taxation 
avoidance agreements with countries in the region, the Board of 
Foreign Trade (BOFT) said Thursday [12 May]. 
  BOFT officials said the board has held consultations on how 
to avoid double taxation with Malaysia, Vietnam, Indonesia and 
Thailand. Although differences remain, the officials expressed 
hope that agreement could be signed soon. 
  Meanwhile, Taiwan is also expected to ask the nations to 
sign 
more far-reaching taxation agreements in the future. 
  The Finance Ministry has already evaluated the impact on 
Taiwan's tax revenue and trade relations if the expanded 
agreements are signed. The ministry has also mapped out a 
taxation agreement draft to help speed up consultations on the 
issue. 

