<H3> <TI>   Buddhists Reassured on Post-1997 Prospects for Religion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Buddhists Reassured on Post-1997 Prospects for Religion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1005125194 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in Chinese 1340 GMT 
9 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK1005125194 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>
<F P=105>  Chinese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By staff reporter Dong Huifeng (5516 2585 1496): "Chen </F>
Ziying Says People Should Rest Assured of the Prospects of 
Religions in Hong Kong After 1997"] 
  [Text] Beijing, 9 May (ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE) -- Chen 
Ziying, deputy director of the State Council's Hong Kong and 
Macao Affairs Office, met today with a visiting delegation from 
the Hong Kong Buddhist Association, headed by Rev Kok-kwong, and 
expressed deep appreciation for the Hong Kong Buddhist 
Association's benevolent activities over the past 50 years since 
its founding. He asked the Buddhists in Hong Kong to rest 
assured of the prospects for religions in Hong Kong after 1997. 
  Chen Ziying said that, according to the Basic Law, the 
future 
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region [SAR] Government will 
not impose any restriction on religious freedom. People with 
religious beliefs, including Buddhists, will be able to openly 
carry out missionary work and hold various religious activities 
that are not in violation of SAR laws. 
  Temples, hospitals, and other rights and properties of 
religious organizations will not be affected, and will be 
protected by law. 
  In addition, religious organizations and individuals in Hong 
Kong may continue to maintain and develop relations with their 
counterpart organizations and individuals in other areas. 
  Chen Ziying said that between the Hong Kong and mainland 
Buddhist organizations, Buddhists should show mutual respect 
before the Buddha, and there will be no subordinative 
relationship between the two sides. The religious circles in 
Hong Kong and the mainland are welcome to visit each other 
frequently so that they can increase exchanges. 
  Zhao Bingxin, director of the Hong Kong Social and Cultural 
Affairs Department of the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office, 
was present at the meeting. 
  In the evening, Chen Ziying and Zhao Bingxin invited the 
12-member delegation headed by Rev Kok-kwong to the Hong 
Kong-Macao Center. 

</TEXT>

