<F P=100> HONG KONG &amp; MACAO </F>
<F P=101> Hong Kong </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chief Secretary Rejects Proposal on Civil Servants' Status </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chief Secretary Rejects Proposal on Civil Servants' Status </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1105061194 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST in English 
11 May 94 p 6 </F>

<F P=103> HK1105061194 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Linda Choy] </F>
  [Text] The head of the civil service, Anson Chan Pang 
On-sang, yesterday warned any attempts to destabilise the system 
would be resisted. She also rejected a proposal for civil 
servants to indicate before 1997 if they would be willing to 
serve the Special Administrative Region government. 
  Mrs Chan, the Chief Secretary, said arrangements for the 
continuity of the civil service had been set out in the Joint 
Declaration and the Basic Law. 
  "Indeed senior Chinese officials, including the Director of 
the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office, have already repeatedly 
assured Hong Kong civil servants on this point," she said. "The 
continuity of service provisions are very clear and we do not 
believe that any further action is required." 
  The political sub-group of the Preliminary Working Committee 
recently proposed that civil servants should indicate their 
post-1997 plans. The proposal was criticised as a form of 
political vetting. 
  Mrs Chan said civil servants did not have a political role 
and their duty to serve the community should not alter before or 
after 1997. The civil service would not pursue private agendas 
or promote the policies of individuals, she said. 
  Despite China's refusal to discuss the line-up of senior 
civil servants, Mrs Chan said the Government believed a dialogue 
should begin as soon as possible. Only 22 positions would be 
affected by requirements, regarding the nationality of civil 
servants, in the Joint Declaration and the Basic Law, she said. 
  In the meantime, the Government would continue to fill the 
most senior government posts with local officers while adopting 
measures to restore the confidence of civil servants. 

</TEXT>

