<F P=100> Near East &amp; South Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian Qichen Calls For Dialogue To Resolve Gulf Problems </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Qian Qichen Calls For Dialogue To Resolve Gulf Problems </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   HK1205070394 Beijing CHINA DAILY in English 12 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> HK1205070394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing CHINA DAILY </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Chang Hong: "Qian Seeks Immediate Cease-Fire in Yemen"] </F>
  [Text] Vice-premier and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen 
yesterday called for an immediate cease-fire and peaceful 
settlement to the civil strife in Yemen. "China is seriously 
concerned with the worsening situation in Yemen and deeply 
grieved by the huge loss in lives and property there," he said. 
"We sincerely hope that both the South and the North can remain 
cool-headed, exercise restraint, stop fighting immediately and 
resolve their disputes through consultation and dialogue," he 
said, adding that China hopes domestic stability is quickly 
restored. 
  Qian made the remarks yesterday in Beijing during a meeting 
with Fahim bin Sultan al-Qasimi, secretary-general of the Gulf 
Cooperation Council (GCC). 
  Qian said China hopes to continue to strengthen ties with 
the 
GCC adding that increased exchanges in recent years have been 
very beneficial. He also said the economies of China and Gulf 
countries are complementary and there is a bright future for 
cooperation. 
  In the Gulf, Qian said China appreciates the GCC's efforts 
to 
maintain regional peace and stability. "China believes that the 
unsettled questions in the Gulf region have to be solved through 
consultation and dialogue among the parties concerned on the 
basis of the UN Security Council resolutions," he said. 
  This will help quickly restore peace and stability and allow 
the war-torn countries to develop their national economies, 
improve peoples' livelihoods and cultivate regional 
co-operation, he said. 
  Qian also said China has done a great deal and will continue 
to work with Gulf nations and the international community to 
this end. Al-Qasimi said the Gulf countries want to develop 
long-term and friendly relations with China, adding that the two 
share similar views on many world and regional issues. 
  On Tuesday Qian met with former U.S. Secretary of State 
Henry 
Kissinger in Beijing. 
  The two exchanged views on regional and global issues and 
Sino-US bilateral relations. 
  After the meeting, Qian hosted a dinner in honour of 
Kissinger and his party. 
  Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister Liu Huaqiu attended both 
occasions. 
  Kissinger arrived in Beijing on Tuesday afternoon to 
participate in the International Symposium on the Strategy of 
China's Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation at the invitation 
of the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Co-operation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

